<TITLE> Poland seeks to pull troops from Iraq by Oct 2008 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WARSAW, Dec 18 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Poland's new government asked the president on Tuesday to approve plans under which the country's 900 troops in Iraq would pull out by October next year. Prime Minister Donald Tusk has clashed with conservative President Lech Kaczynski, who has opposed a troop withdrawal so soon. The request for a final extension of Poland's military mission in Iraq until October 2008 was presented as a compromise. Tusk, who defeated the president's twin brother, former Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski, in October elections, pledged in his inaugural address last month to withdraw Polish soldiers from Iraq next year. Some of his deputies had said this could take place as soon as mid-2008. "Polish soldiers and the rest of the personnel will take actions related to concluding the mission that is a part of the international stabilisation force in the Republic of Iraq," the government said in a statement. Poland, the largest ex-communist NATO and European Union member, backed the 2003 US-led invasion of Iraq and had as many as 2,500 troops on the ground at one point. President Kaczynski, who has promoted a strong pro-US policy in the face of a more EU-friendly approach of the new centre-right government, has criticised Tusk's plan and some aides have said he may not back the government's proposal. But the president's National Security Advisor Wladyslaw Stasiak, who met Defence Minister Bogdan Klich on Monday, indicated Kaczynski might agree to the new proposal. "Right now there is a bigger possibility for the president to respond positively. This is a better proposal," Stasiak said in a television interview. Tusk has said that without the president's approval for the final extension Polish soldiers would need to quickly leave Iraq when their latest mission expires at the end of the year. He added that such a move would be nearly impossible because of the complicated logistics of moving troops and equipme
